95
00:05:37,338 --> 00:05:39,204
            narrator:           
 originating in the middle east,

96
00:05:39,206 --> 00:05:42,140
   pita bread has been around   
     for thousands of years.    

97
00:05:42,142 --> 00:05:46,278
 today, its popularity continues
    to grow around the globe.   

98
00:05:46,280 --> 00:05:48,881
       part of its appeal       
       is its versatility.      

99
00:05:48,883 --> 00:05:51,150
        people can stuff        
      their pita's pockets,     

100
00:05:51,152 --> 00:05:54,486
   use it as a sandwich wrap,   
    or slice it for dipping.    

101
00:05:57,892 --> 00:05:59,557
     pita bread may be flat,    

102
00:05:59,559 --> 00:06:01,760
      but that doesn't mean     
          it's boring.          

103
00:06:01,762 --> 00:06:03,829
       anyone can use pita      
       to make any number       

104
00:06:03,831 --> 00:06:08,233
         of interesting         
     lunchtime combinations.    

105
00:06:08,235 --> 00:06:12,037
    making pita bread starts    
    with silos full of flour.   

106
00:06:12,039 --> 00:06:15,774
  a blower system delivers the  
  flour to an automated sifter. 

107
00:06:15,776 --> 00:06:18,911
   the sifter shakes the flour  
  through three levels of mesh  

108
00:06:18,913 --> 00:06:21,046
    to filter out impurities.   

109
00:06:21,048 --> 00:06:24,783
         magnets extract        
     any metal contaminants.    

110
00:06:24,785 --> 00:06:28,453
    workers prepare a pre-mix   
     of sugar, salt, yeast,     

111
00:06:28,455 --> 00:06:30,122
       and preservatives.       

112
00:06:30,124 --> 00:06:32,724
 they combine these ingredients 
      with the sifted flour     

113
00:06:32,726 --> 00:06:35,928
  in a big mixer and add water. 

114
00:06:35,930 --> 00:06:38,197
      the mixer is equipped     
       with numerous bars       

115
00:06:38,199 --> 00:06:42,334
    that rotate horizontally    
    to blend the ingredients.   

116
00:06:43,203 --> 00:06:47,139
  the operator opens the mixer  
   and spins it one more time   

117
00:06:47,141 --> 00:06:49,541
 to eject the dough into a bin. 

118
00:06:53,080 --> 00:06:56,948
        he rolls the bin        
      to the next station.      

119
00:06:56,950 --> 00:07:00,219
       here the pita dough      
       goes into a hopper.      

120
00:07:00,221 --> 00:07:02,754
         and from there,        
     it drops into a machine    

121
00:07:02,756 --> 00:07:04,356
     called a dough divider.    

122
00:07:04,358 --> 00:07:10,029
                     ♪          

123
00:07:10,031 --> 00:07:15,000
  this machine turns big chunks 
 of dough into many small blobs.

124
00:07:15,002 --> 00:07:18,703
 to do this, it forces the dough
      through a round hole,     

125
00:07:18,705 --> 00:07:24,043
 and a guillotine blade chops it
    to the correct thickness.   

126
00:07:24,045 --> 00:07:27,246
 the dough blobs ride a conveyor
     and pass under a roller    

127
00:07:27,248 --> 00:07:29,982
       that flattens them.      

128
00:07:29,984 --> 00:07:33,986
  flour from an overhead sifter 
      dusts the dough blobs     

129
00:07:33,988 --> 00:07:38,189
   to keep them from sticking   
        to the machinery.       

130
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:40,058
   each one of these flattened  
           dough blobs          

131
00:07:40,060 --> 00:07:41,927
 will eventually become a pita. 

132
00:07:45,199 --> 00:07:46,999
    the round pieces of dough   
            now ride            

133
00:07:47,001 --> 00:07:49,668
  a conveyor up to a warm zone. 

134
00:07:49,670 --> 00:07:53,405
  over a period of 15 minutes,  
       the yeast ferments,      

135
00:07:53,407 --> 00:07:56,074
   causing the dough to rise.   

136
00:07:56,076 --> 00:07:57,943
out of the fermentation station,

137
00:07:57,945 --> 00:08:03,215
        a roller flattens       
 the pita dough segments again. 

138
00:08:03,217 --> 00:08:05,617
        they're now ready       
     to be rolled very thin     

139
00:08:05,619 --> 00:08:07,886
 in a process known as sheeting.

140
00:08:10,224 --> 00:08:13,691
     the next roller presses    
  the pita dough much thinner.  

141
00:08:13,693 --> 00:08:15,360
   rolling it in one direction  

142
00:08:15,362 --> 00:08:17,896
    makes the dough segments    
          oval-shaped.          

143
00:08:21,101 --> 00:08:23,301
 the oval pitas ride by a pusher

144
00:08:23,303 --> 00:08:28,239
      that now shoves them      
    towards the final roller.   

145
00:08:28,241 --> 00:08:31,910
 it rolls the dough in the other
direction to round out the shape

146
00:08:31,912 --> 00:08:33,579
    and make it even thinner.   

147
00:08:37,318 --> 00:08:39,184
    perfectly round and thin,   

148
00:08:39,186 --> 00:08:43,055
   the pitas now travel up to   
 another fermentation operation.

149
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:47,926
     inside, the temperature    
           is toasty.           

150
00:08:47,928 --> 00:08:50,329
  it's warm enough to reawaken  
            the yeast           

151
00:08:50,331 --> 00:08:52,598
       and cause the dough      
         to rise again.         

152
00:08:56,002 --> 00:08:59,471
  conveyors move in criss-cross 
  directions to take the pitas  

153
00:08:59,473 --> 00:09:01,206
         back and forth.        

154
00:09:01,208 --> 00:09:06,144
    this zig-zagging journey    
     lasts about 15 minutes.    

155
00:09:06,146 --> 00:09:08,413
      when the pitas emerge     
        from the chamber,       

156
00:09:08,415 --> 00:09:12,150
     they have thickened up     
         substantially.         

157
00:09:12,152 --> 00:09:15,354
     they head into an oven     
    where the magic happens.    

158
00:09:15,356 --> 00:09:18,490
    the oven's temperature is   
           between 750          

159
00:09:18,492 --> 00:09:20,959
   and 930 degrees fahrenheit.  

160
00:09:20,961 --> 00:09:23,495
         they spend just        
        15 seconds in it.       

161
00:09:23,497 --> 00:09:26,231
    this flash-baking causes    
     the water in the dough     

162
00:09:26,233 --> 00:09:27,632
        to turn to steam.       

163
00:09:27,634 --> 00:09:31,903
   the steam puffs the pitas,   
    creating pockets inside.    

164
00:09:31,905 --> 00:09:33,238
      the pitas then travel     

165
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:36,040
          on conveyors          
   for a 20 minute cool down.   

166
00:09:36,042 --> 00:09:38,977
   as they cool, they deflate.  

167
00:09:38,979 --> 00:09:42,181
 the process has created pockets
          in the pitas.         

168
00:09:42,183 --> 00:09:43,648
        once sliced open,       

169
00:09:43,650 --> 00:09:47,319
   the pockets can be stuffed   
      to create sandwiches.     

170
00:09:47,321 --> 00:09:52,056
     workers stack the pitas    
     six high for packaging.    

171
00:09:52,058 --> 00:09:54,659
   the next conveyor delivers   
   the stacks into the clutch   

172
00:09:54,661 --> 00:09:58,130
      of an automated arm.      

173
00:09:58,132 --> 00:10:01,266
   just ahead, a burst of air   
           opens a bag          

174
00:10:01,268 --> 00:10:03,935
       and the arm inserts      
       the pitas into it.       

175
00:10:03,937 --> 00:10:09,341
   at the same time, it pushes  
the bag on to the next conveyor.

176
00:10:09,343 --> 00:10:12,544
 moving forward, another device 
      automatically twists      

177
00:10:12,546 --> 00:10:15,347
    the open end of the bag.    

178
00:10:15,349 --> 00:10:17,482
       the device applies       
       a plastic lock tab       

179
00:10:17,484 --> 00:10:23,088
 to the twisted end of the bag, 
 sealing the pita breads inside.

180
00:10:23,090 --> 00:10:25,557
        the bags pass by        
        a metal detector,       

181
00:10:25,559 --> 00:10:28,026
  and then they're on their way 
       to the supermarket.      

182
00:10:32,433 --> 00:10:36,702
    this pita bread has taken   
 45 minutes to make and package,

183
00:10:36,704 --> 00:10:40,472
   but it should enable lunch   
 to come together very quickly. 

184
00:10:48,248 --> 00:10:53,719
                     ♪          

185
00:10:53,721 --> 00:10:55,253
            narrator:           
   installing exhaust headers   

186
00:10:55,255 --> 00:10:58,190
      will add extra power      
      from a car's engine.      

187
00:10:58,192 --> 00:11:00,726
   they bolt on to the engine,  
      giving each cylinder      

188
00:11:00,728 --> 00:11:03,261
      its own exhaust pipe      
    leading to the collector,   

189
00:11:03,263 --> 00:11:06,532
   which connects to the car's  
       main exhaust pipe.       

190
00:11:06,534 --> 00:11:09,334
   that's more efficient than   
having all the cylinders exhaust

191
00:11:09,336 --> 00:11:11,203
     into a common manifold.    

192
00:11:13,741 --> 00:11:17,542
a header draws out significantly
    more spent exhaust gasses   

193
00:11:17,544 --> 00:11:20,746
 after combustion, leaving room 
      for a greater amount      

194
00:11:20,748 --> 00:11:22,281
    of new gas and fresh air    

195
00:11:22,283 --> 00:11:26,685
      to enter the cylinder     
 for the next combustion cycle. 

196
00:11:26,687 --> 00:11:29,888
    headers are made of steel   
       or stainless steel.      

197
00:11:29,890 --> 00:11:33,358
   a worker uses a roll cutter  
   to slice tubes into nearly   

198
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:37,562
       6-inch-long pieces       
   for the header's collector.  

199
00:11:37,564 --> 00:11:39,364
    a forming tool on a press   

200
00:11:39,366 --> 00:11:42,901
       stretches one side       
    of the collector outward.   

201
00:11:42,903 --> 00:11:47,372
 then the worker places the same
 side on an end-forming machine,

202
00:11:47,374 --> 00:11:50,642
      which shapes it like      
       a four-leaf clover.      

203
00:11:50,644 --> 00:11:53,645
     he slips a flange over     
        the unshaped side       

204
00:11:53,647 --> 00:11:57,115
 and widens that side to create 
        the ball portion        

205
00:11:57,117 --> 00:11:59,784
     of the gasketless ball     
      and socket connection     

206
00:11:59,786 --> 00:12:01,954
 to the car's main exhaust pipe.

207
00:12:04,658 --> 00:12:08,060
    meanwhile, another worker   
    roll cuts narrower tubes    

208
00:12:08,062 --> 00:12:12,530
into 32-inch-long pieces to make
   the header's primary tubes,  

209
00:12:12,532 --> 00:12:17,669
 the ones that attach at the top
     to engine's cylinders.     

210
00:12:17,671 --> 00:12:20,339
     a worker slides a tube     
        on to a mandrel,        

211
00:12:20,341 --> 00:12:22,808
    then the computer-guided    
         mandrel bender         

212
00:12:22,810 --> 00:12:25,343
 bends the tube in four places. 

213
00:12:25,345 --> 00:12:28,013
  the mandrel fills the inside  
           of the tube          

214
00:12:28,015 --> 00:12:30,949
   just up to the bend point,   
    preventing the tube from    

215
00:12:30,951 --> 00:12:34,753
    compressing or collapsing   
         under pressure.        

216
00:12:34,755 --> 00:12:38,156
 the header they're making here 
 is for a four-cylinder engine, 

217
00:12:38,158 --> 00:12:40,826
  so it has four primary tubes. 

218
00:12:40,828 --> 00:12:43,662
    an eight-cylinder engine    
   requires a pair of headers,  

219
00:12:43,664 --> 00:12:45,163
  whereas a six-cylinder engine 

220
00:12:45,165 --> 00:12:49,567
         requires a pair        
     of three-tube headers.     

221
00:12:49,569 --> 00:12:51,969
     a worker trims the bent    
          primary tubes         

222
00:12:51,971 --> 00:12:54,506
     to the required length     
         with a bandsaw.        

223
00:12:58,579 --> 00:13:01,913
   the sawed edges of the tube  
           are ragged,          

224
00:13:01,915 --> 00:13:04,516
        so the next step        
    is to grind them smooth.    

225
00:13:04,518 --> 00:13:09,654
                     ♪          

226
00:13:09,656 --> 00:13:13,591
    after grinding, the edge    
   no longer looks like this.   

227
00:13:13,593 --> 00:13:19,464
                     ♪          

228
00:13:19,466 --> 00:13:21,533
    workers heat the top end    
           of the tube          

229
00:13:21,535 --> 00:13:24,069
          with a torch          
      to soften the steel.      

230
00:13:24,071 --> 00:13:29,674
                     ♪          

231
00:13:29,676 --> 00:13:33,145
       they place the end       
  into an end-forming machine.  

232
00:13:33,147 --> 00:13:34,546
   the machine shapes the end   

233
00:13:34,548 --> 00:13:37,149
    to match the top profile    
        of the cylinder,        

234
00:13:37,151 --> 00:13:40,818
        to which the tube       
        will be mounted.        

235
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:43,955
     cylinder profiles vary     
     from engine to engine,     

236
00:13:43,957 --> 00:13:47,459
    so workers simply change    
the forming tool on the machine.

237
00:13:51,498 --> 00:13:54,700
   a worker clamps the header   
      flange with its four      

238
00:13:54,702 --> 00:13:58,170
       exhaust ports on to      
  an assembly jig and positions 

239
00:13:58,172 --> 00:14:02,774
         the top end of         
  a primary tube in each port.  

240
00:14:02,776 --> 00:14:04,376
   he inserts the bottom ends   

241
00:14:04,378 --> 00:14:08,113
into the four-leaf-clover-shaped
           collector.           

242
00:14:10,517 --> 00:14:13,051
    he then welds the top end   
          of each tube          

243
00:14:13,053 --> 00:14:16,587
       to its exhaust port      
      on the header flange.     

244
00:14:16,589 --> 00:14:19,257
       then he welds a tag      
      with the company name     

245
00:14:19,259 --> 00:14:21,026
     on to one of the tubes.    

246
00:14:23,530 --> 00:14:26,264
        finally, he welds       
   the bottom end of the tubes  

247
00:14:26,266 --> 00:14:28,133
        to the collector.       

248
00:14:28,135 --> 00:14:32,671
                     ♪          

249
00:14:32,673 --> 00:14:35,407
 the header's three sections -- 
         flange, tubes,         

250
00:14:35,409 --> 00:14:39,611
 and collector -- are now fused.

251
00:14:39,613 --> 00:14:42,414
 the worker grinds down the weld
        around the ports        

252
00:14:42,416 --> 00:14:45,484
    until it's nearly flush.    

253
00:14:45,486 --> 00:14:48,553
    the remaining bit of weld   
  material encircling the port  

254
00:14:48,555 --> 00:14:51,123
            will act            
  as a seal to prevent leakage. 

255
00:14:55,495 --> 00:14:58,229
       during the welding,      
   some welding material drips  

256
00:14:58,231 --> 00:15:01,233
    into the header flange's    
            openings,           

257
00:15:01,235 --> 00:15:03,968
        so a worker reams       
   the bolt holes with a drill  

258
00:15:03,970 --> 00:15:06,204
           and grinds           
     the edges of each port.    

259
00:15:09,176 --> 00:15:11,776
     he mounts the header on    
   the corresponding engine's   

260
00:15:11,778 --> 00:15:16,248
 cylinder head to make sure bolt
 holes are sufficiently cleared.

261
00:15:16,250 --> 00:15:20,918
  then he runs a torch over all 
 the joints to check the welds. 

262
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:23,855
  the flame would shoot through 
       any hole in a weld,      

263
00:15:23,857 --> 00:15:26,525
   alerting them to repair it.  

264
00:15:29,263 --> 00:15:33,798
 this factory applies one of two
finishes on its exhaust headers.

265
00:15:33,800 --> 00:15:37,068
     the basic one is a coat    
   of black water-based paint   

266
00:15:37,070 --> 00:15:39,537
    sprayed on and air-dried.   

267
00:15:39,539 --> 00:15:41,806
    it prevents surface rust    
          from forming          

268
00:15:41,808 --> 00:15:44,009
  while the part is warehoused. 

269
00:15:44,011 --> 00:15:47,879
   the higher-end finish is an  
aerospace-grade ceramic coating,

270
00:15:47,881 --> 00:15:50,415
  available in black or silver. 

271
00:15:50,417 --> 00:15:53,752
  this baked-on finish protects 
      the headers from rust     

272
00:15:53,754 --> 00:15:56,822
         for many years         
  of high-performance driving.  

273
00:16:05,766 --> 00:16:10,735
                     ♪          

274
00:16:10,737 --> 00:16:12,571
            narrator:           
    this may look like ivory,   

275
00:16:12,573 --> 00:16:14,639
  but it's actually limestone.  

276
00:16:14,641 --> 00:16:17,242
       it looks as though       
  it's a sculpted work of art,  

277
00:16:17,244 --> 00:16:19,177
    but it's actually molded.   

278
00:16:19,179 --> 00:16:21,379
  how does one mold limestone?  

279
00:16:21,381 --> 00:16:25,316
   200 years ago, some people   
   in france figured out how,   

280
00:16:25,318 --> 00:16:31,222
 and their descendents are still
molding limestone artwork today.

281
00:16:31,224 --> 00:16:34,860
   this unique art form exists  
   because, two centuries ago,  

282
00:16:34,862 --> 00:16:39,664
  a family in france discovered 
   springs amid volcanic rock,  

283
00:16:39,666 --> 00:16:43,334
   springs with water so rich   
      in calcium carbonate      

284
00:16:43,336 --> 00:16:45,470
  that it petrified into stone. 

285
00:16:45,472 --> 00:16:48,139
       that is limestone.       

286
00:16:48,141 --> 00:16:51,409
  the family carved out caves,  
       then invented a way      

287
00:16:51,411 --> 00:16:55,680
to capture the calcium carbonate
  and mold sculptures with it.  

288
00:16:55,682 --> 00:16:59,918
  the descendents of the family 
 continue that tradition today. 

289
00:16:59,920 --> 00:17:03,722
    the springwater contains    
 two grams of calcium carbonate 

290
00:17:03,724 --> 00:17:06,558
       per liter and a lot      
         of iron oxide,         

291
00:17:06,560 --> 00:17:08,826
  which makes the water orange. 

292
00:17:08,828 --> 00:17:10,962
      the original troughs      
        direct the water        

293
00:17:10,964 --> 00:17:13,498
  on to a bed of wood shavings. 

294
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:15,833
        the shavings trap       
         the iron oxide,        

295
00:17:15,835 --> 00:17:20,105
and the calcium carbonate floats
         to the surface.        

296
00:17:20,107 --> 00:17:22,707
        in the workshop,        
   the owner of the company --  

297
00:17:22,709 --> 00:17:25,310
     the seventh generation     
    of the founding family --   

298
00:17:25,312 --> 00:17:26,844
         makes the mold.        

299
00:17:26,846 --> 00:17:29,047
    he heats something called   
          gutta-percha          

300
00:17:29,049 --> 00:17:31,649
        in a pot of water       
        to soften it up.        

301
00:17:31,651 --> 00:17:34,185
 gutta-percha is a natural latex

302
00:17:34,187 --> 00:17:36,454
        made from the sap       
       of the gutta tree.       

303
00:17:36,456 --> 00:17:39,457
  once it's soft, he weighs out 
       the required amount      

304
00:17:39,459 --> 00:17:41,960
      using the workshop's      
         original scale.        

305
00:17:45,265 --> 00:17:48,466
 then he kneads it to force out 
           trapped air          

306
00:17:48,468 --> 00:17:50,201
   and make it more malleable.  

307
00:17:53,206 --> 00:17:57,375
  after forming it into a ball, 
  he places it in an old press  

308
00:17:57,377 --> 00:17:59,811
 made my his great-grandfather. 

309
00:17:59,813 --> 00:18:02,013
        the press shapes        
        the gutta-percha        

310
00:18:02,015 --> 00:18:05,450
   into a rectangle measuring   
         7-by-10 inches.        

311
00:18:09,155 --> 00:18:11,622
   after cooling in the press   
         for 30 minutes,        

312
00:18:11,624 --> 00:18:13,358
  the gutta-percha has hardened 

313
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:17,429
     just enough to maintain    
     the rectangular shape.     

314
00:18:17,431 --> 00:18:19,163
  he removes it from the press  

315
00:18:19,165 --> 00:18:23,367
 and places a silicone-designed 
        template on top.        

316
00:18:23,369 --> 00:18:26,704
    he cuts the gutta-percha    
  to the shape of the template. 

317
00:18:26,706 --> 00:18:32,243
                     ♪          

318
00:18:32,245 --> 00:18:34,980
   he places the gutta-percha   
       on top of a pattern      

319
00:18:34,982 --> 00:18:38,449
      created by an artist.     

320
00:18:38,451 --> 00:18:41,118
     he places the template     
      on the gutta-percha,      

321
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:43,455
      then a plank of wood      
         on top of that.        

322
00:18:46,192 --> 00:18:50,095
   he puts the entire assembly  
    under an old screw press.   

323
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:57,602
    an hour later, he removes   
   the assembly from the press  

324
00:18:57,604 --> 00:19:00,105
and gently separates the layers.

325
00:19:02,275 --> 00:19:05,610
    the artwork design is now   
  transferred from the pattern  

326
00:19:05,612 --> 00:19:07,545
      to the gutta-percha.      

327
00:19:07,547 --> 00:19:11,416
    he sets it aside to cool    
        to a hard state.        

328
00:19:12,285 --> 00:19:15,286
      when the work of art      
   is either too wide or high   

329
00:19:15,288 --> 00:19:17,322
           to fit into          
  the traditional screw press,  

330
00:19:17,324 --> 00:19:20,425
    the artisan then sculpts    
    the pattern out of clay.    

331
00:19:20,427 --> 00:19:25,429
 once the clay hardens, he coats
it in silicone to make the mold.

332
00:19:25,431 --> 00:19:28,833
     this modern mold-making    
   technique is a bit trickier  

333
00:19:28,835 --> 00:19:31,102
        because silicone        
        can't be reheated       

334
00:19:31,104 --> 00:19:33,338
 and reworked like gutta-percha.

335
00:19:35,775 --> 00:19:37,909
    the silicone takes about    
            24 hours            

336
00:19:37,911 --> 00:19:40,911
 to harden into a flexible mold.

337
00:19:40,913 --> 00:19:43,915
   a silicone mold can be used  
           only once.           

338
00:19:43,917 --> 00:19:47,585
  and because it's so flexible, 
 it has to sit on a support tray

339
00:19:47,587 --> 00:19:52,256
    so that it doesn't buckle   
      when filled or moved.     

340
00:19:52,258 --> 00:19:54,592
      now it's time to mold     
         the limestone.         

341
00:19:54,594 --> 00:19:57,195
      a craftsman positions     
      the molds under these     

342
00:19:57,197 --> 00:19:59,597
  liquid limestone waterfalls.  

343
00:19:59,599 --> 00:20:03,334
 the carbonic gas in the liquid 
      gradually evaporates,     

344
00:20:03,336 --> 00:20:08,273
leaving accumulating deposits of
 calcium carbonate in the molds.

345
00:20:08,275 --> 00:20:12,277
   an artisan moves every mold  
     to a new position daily    

346
00:20:12,279 --> 00:20:15,947
   so that the dripping water   
      hits all parts of it.     

347
00:20:15,949 --> 00:20:19,483
 artwork just one 1/5 of an inch
         thick requires         

348
00:20:19,485 --> 00:20:21,819
 six months under the fountain. 

349
00:20:21,821 --> 00:20:25,924
  artwork 4/5 of an inch thick  
       requires two years.      

350
00:20:28,161 --> 00:20:31,696
to extract the limestone artwork
    from a traditional mold,    

351
00:20:31,698 --> 00:20:34,098
     the artisan immerses it    
          in hot water          

352
00:20:34,100 --> 00:20:38,236
  to soften the gutta-percha so 
 that he can gently peel it off.

353
00:20:38,238 --> 00:20:40,305
     every intricate detail     
          of the design         

354
00:20:40,307 --> 00:20:44,909
       in the gutta-percha      
 is now replicated in limestone.

355
00:20:44,911 --> 00:20:49,848
  this molded rock is as strong 
       and hard as marble.      

356
00:20:49,850 --> 00:20:52,717
      to extra the artwork      
      from a silicone mold,     

357
00:20:52,719 --> 00:20:57,355
 an artisan removes the support 
tray and lifts off the silicone.

358
00:20:57,357 --> 00:21:01,259
  the company has more than 500 
    artwork patterns in stock   

359
00:21:01,261 --> 00:21:04,328
      dating back to 1821.      

360
00:21:04,330 --> 00:21:07,131
  not all the molded limestone  
         looks the same.        

361
00:21:07,133 --> 00:21:10,734
     the artisans can tailor    
  the shade from white to ivory 

362
00:21:10,736 --> 00:21:13,004
         by controlling         
       how much iron oxide      

363
00:21:13,006 --> 00:21:15,406
   they remove from the water.  

